  "text": "Django's CSRF protection is implemented across multiple modules forming a complete validation chain. The primary entry point is CsrfViewMiddleware (django/middleware/csrf.py:165-484), which is a MiddlewareMixin that processes all incoming requests. In the process_view() method (line 414-470), the middleware checks for CSRF exemption, checks the HTTP method (only protecting non-safe methods), verifies the Origin/Referer headers, and then calls _check_token() to validate the CSRF token.\n\nThe _check_token() method (line 349-399) orchestrates the token validation by first retrieving the CSRF secret using _get_secret() (line 221-251). The secret is obtained from either the session (if CSRF_USE_SESSIONS is enabled) or from cookies. The token format is validated using _check_token_format() (line 130-140), which ensures the token has correct length (either CSRF_TOKEN_LENGTH or CSRF_SECRET_LENGTH) and contains only allowed characters. The actual token comparison happens in _does_token_match() (line 143-157), which unmasks masked tokens if necessary and uses constant_time_compare() for the comparison to prevent timing attacks.\n\nThe token generation and masking logic uses _mask_cipher_secret() (line 59-68) and _unmask_cipher_token() (line 71-81) functions. The masking scheme adds a random mask to the secret and applies a cipher operation, which is then reversed during validation.\n\nThe csrf_protect decorator (django/views/decorators/csrf.py:7) is created using decorator_from_middleware(CsrfViewMiddleware) from django/utils/decorators.py (line 114-120). This decorator applies the same CSRF protection on a per-view basis. Additional decorators include requires_csrf_token and ensure_csrf_cookie, which use subclasses _EnsureCsrfToken and _EnsureCsrfCookie that override the _reject() method to avoid raising errors while still ensuring token availability.\n\nTiming attack prevention is implemented through constant_time_compare() in django/utils/crypto.py (line 65-67), which wraps secrets.compare_digest() to perform byte-by-byte comparison in constant time, preventing attackers from inferring token validity through timing analysis.\n\nWhen CSRF validation fails, the middleware calls _reject() (line 209-219), which retrieves the failure view using _get_failure_view() and renders the csrf_failure() view from django/views/csrf.py (line 22-80), displaying a 403 Forbidden response with an appropriate error message.\n\nSecurity checks for CSRF configuration are performed in django/core/checks/security/csrf.py, which validates that CsrfViewMiddleware is enabled and that CSRF_COOKIE_SECURE is set to True for enhanced security."
}

